diff:1619206397:1619206397:=1,51d0%0a%3c :Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild%0a%3c :Essential: {Category.LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild$:essential}%0a%3c :Title: Discrimination Against the AAVE Accent%0a%3c :Author: rachelc%0a%3c :Section: A%0a%3c :Completed: 23.04.2021 - 12:33%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25blue%25 '''Comments for student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c Summary: \\%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summary]]%0a%3c %0a%3c A quora commenter shows discrimination against the AAVE accent%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#summaryends]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c I recently came across this quora question, which asks “As a non-native speaker, which English accents do you think sound best or worst, or are most difficult to understand?” (https://www.quora.com/As-a-non-native-speaker-which-English-accents-do-you-think-sound-best-or-worst-or-are-most-difficult-to-understand). I thought that this question could produce some problematic answers, and in particular the response by Paolo Ferrari caught my attention. He says that one of the accents he “hates the most” is the Afro-American accent because “Afro-American pronunciation sounds to me ghastly so imprecise and approximate as to make any attempt for understanding vane.”%0a%3c %0a%3c This comment really struck me due to its prescriptive nature. Instead of making a meaningful comparison of the AAVE accent to the Standard American accent, he chooses to characterize the AAVE accent as “ghastly” and “imprecise.” While he doesn’t go into specifics about what aspect of the accent he finds imprecise, I would venture to guess that he could be referring to the reduction of consonant clusters at the ends of words (for instance [tɛst] becomes [tɛs]), the swapping for the ‘θ’ and ‘ð’ sounds for ‘f’ and ‘d’, respectively (“math”: [mæθ] → [mæf] and the: [ðə] → [də]), or exchanging “ɹ” for “ʌ” at the ends of words (“sister”: [sɪstɹ] → [sɪstʌ]), among other AAVE characteristics. %0a%3c %0a%3c If you consider AAVE through the lens of Standard American English being the “correct” way to speak, some of the characteristics of AAVE may seem “imprecise” or “approximate” as the commenter suggests. However, Standard American English is not the “correct” way to speak, it is simply “a” way to speak, as is AAVE, and the commenter’s description of AAVE as being “ghastly” shows a clear bias that the commenter has against this dialect.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.hawaii.edu/satocenter/langnet/definitions/aave.html#:~:text=At%2520the%2520end%2520of%2520a%2520word%252C%2520th%2520is%2520often%2520pronounced,'%253B%2520mont%2520for%2520'month'. %0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
